2. Do some data cleaning.

# Drop some columns which only have a few observations
# There are four types of target variables
# However, only biopsy is a golden standard in the clinical diagnosis of cervical cancer, so we will drop the others
# There are some risk factors which several variables describe, therefore only keep one for each
data<-data[,c(1,2,3,4,6,9,11,13,29,30,31,36)]
data<-na.omit(data)

4. Since the target variable is categorical, logistic regression will be an approparite model to do prediction.

Do datatype transformation

Generate the logistic model according the result of bestglm.

# generate the logistic regression model
data3 = data[ , c("STDs..number.", "Dx.HPV")]
data3$Classification = data$y
data3Logit <- glm(Classification ~ STDs..number.+Dx.HPV, data = data3, binomial(link = "logit"))
summary(data3Logit)

Evaluate the logistic model using ROC curve and Area-Under-Curve. The area-under-curve is 0.6346. Since it is less than 0.8, suggest that the model is not very good.

loadPkg("pROC")
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
prob=predict(data3Logit, type = c("response"))
data3$prob=prob
h <- roc(Classification~prob, data=data3)
auc(h) 
## Area under the curve: 0.6346
plot(h)

detach("package:pROC", unload = T)

5. Formulate a KNN model for the data.

# Scale data for KNN to function correctly
scaled.data <- as.data.frame(scale(data[1:8], center=TRUE, scale=TRUE))

# Function to convert categorical variables to numbers for KNN
to_num <- function(x) {as.integer(x)}
scaled.data <- cbind(scaled.data, as.data.frame(sapply(data[,9:11], FUN=to_num)))

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(1000)

# Set training and test data
data_sample <- sample(2, nrow(scaled.data), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.67,0.33))
trainSet <- scaled.data[data_sample==1, 1:11]
testSet <- scaled.data[data_sample==2, 1:11]
trainLabels <- data[data_sample==1, 12]
testLabels <- data[data_sample==2, 12]
loadPkg("FNN")
loadPkg("gmodels")
loadPkg("ggplot2")
# Define a vector to store accuracy for each value of k
accuracy <- c(NULL)
k_values <- seq(from=1, to=20, by=2)   # Sequence of k values to use
for (k in k_values) {
pred <- knn(train=trainSet, test=testSet, cl=trainLabels, k=k)
cancer_pred <- CrossTable(testLabels, pred, prop.chisq=FALSE)
t = table(pred, testLabels)
accu = sum(t[row(t)==col(t)])/sum(t)
print(paste("Accuracy with k =", k, ":", accu))
accuracy <- c(accuracy, accu)
print(paste(""))
print(paste("   ******************************************************   "))
}
